WEBVTT

00:07.408 --> 00:11.812
(wind whistles)

00:11.812 --> 00:14.882
(thunder cracks)

00:19.987 --> 00:22.256
- It's a perfect night
for mystery and horror.

00:22.256 --> 00:26.060
The air itself is
filled with monsters.

00:26.060 --> 00:27.695
- I'm all ears.

00:27.695 --> 00:29.663
Open up your pits of hell.

00:31.532 --> 00:34.202
(ominous music)

00:37.538 --> 00:42.110
- As queer people, we are
considered outside of society

00:43.311 --> 00:47.381
and I think horror is
outside of society.

00:47.381 --> 00:49.850
(ominous music continues)

00:55.389 --> 00:58.058
- Horror stories upset
all the right people.

00:58.058 --> 01:01.595
People who can't
handle ambiguity,

01:01.595 --> 01:06.167
people who can't handle
violence or eroticism,

01:06.167 --> 01:10.271
people who think of the world
in these very clear-cut terms.

01:11.772 --> 01:14.108
(thunder cracks)

01:14.108 --> 01:15.576
- Most Americans are repelled

01:15.576 --> 01:17.945
by the mere notion
of homosexuality.

01:17.945 --> 01:20.981
The CBS News survey shows that
two out of three Americans

01:20.981 --> 01:24.518
look upon homosexuals with
disgust, discomfort, or fear.

01:24.518 --> 01:26.720
(distant scream)

01:26.720 --> 01:27.755
- What was that?

01:27.755 --> 01:29.789
- The main thing
about horror was

01:29.789 --> 01:32.226
that it was exciting
to get scared

01:32.226 --> 01:34.162
and that there was
an honesty to it,

01:34.162 --> 01:36.797
because I was responding
to how my body felt.

01:36.797 --> 01:38.598
So, kind of like porn.

01:38.598 --> 01:40.134
(birds screeching)

01:40.134 --> 01:41.634
- Your blood starts pumping.

01:41.634 --> 01:44.705
There is something very, very
primal about being afraid.

01:46.140 --> 01:48.642
- Horror designed to make
you incredibly uncomfortable.

01:48.642 --> 01:50.178
(Ridley screams)

01:50.178 --> 01:51.712
And I think that queer people

01:51.712 --> 01:53.080
are just generally better
at being uncomfortable.

01:53.080 --> 01:54.815
- Now kindly undo these straps.

01:56.184 --> 01:59.453
- Because queer has
been seen as bad,

01:59.453 --> 02:00.654
has been seen as the other,

02:00.654 --> 02:02.690
of course we're gonna
put anything bad

02:02.690 --> 02:04.592
and anything the
other as the monster.

02:04.592 --> 02:06.426
- I know who I am now, Sam.

02:06.426 --> 02:07.661
(Sam growls)

02:07.661 --> 02:09.062
- You wait till mom
finds out, buddy.

02:09.062 --> 02:10.698
- I always thought of
myself as a monster

02:10.698 --> 02:12.500
or a freak or a weirdo.

02:12.500 --> 02:15.836
- My, I'll bet you monsters
lead interesting lives.

02:15.836 --> 02:20.274
- I'm Frankenstein, I'm
Dracula, I'm Mrs. Danvers.

02:20.274 --> 02:21.909
(suspenseful music)

02:21.909 --> 02:23.110
- So many of us can relate

02:23.110 --> 02:24.578
to being the the
monster in the room.

02:24.578 --> 02:28.382
- I want to walk amongst
the commoners unnoticed.

02:28.382 --> 02:30.418
A prince amongst paupers.

02:30.418 --> 02:32.920
- The reason queer people have
latched onto these monsters

02:32.920 --> 02:36.656
is because we see
in them that society

02:36.656 --> 02:38.892
is always trying
to eradicate us.

02:38.892 --> 02:40.328
(banging on door)

02:40.328 --> 02:42.496
(werewolves screaming)

02:42.496 --> 02:44.632
And we're always
waiting to fight back.

02:44.632 --> 02:46.534
(suspenseful music)
(wood splinters)

02:46.534 --> 02:48.236
- That's how we're
represented in film.

02:48.236 --> 02:49.703
(werewolf howling)

02:49.703 --> 02:50.971
We're the bogeyman.

02:50.971 --> 02:52.139
We're the ones who
are out to get you.

02:52.139 --> 02:54.041
(glass squeaking)

02:54.041 --> 02:57.545
- A flood tide of filth
is engulfing our country

02:57.545 --> 02:59.347
and is threatening to pervert

02:59.347 --> 03:02.115
an entire generation of
our American children.

03:02.115 --> 03:02.950
(Glen screams)

03:02.950 --> 03:06.254
(screaming)

03:06.254 --> 03:08.155
- You sit the fuck down!

03:08.155 --> 03:09.690
(Leatherface whimpers)

03:09.690 --> 03:13.561
- They constantly portray
abnormal sexual behavior.

03:13.561 --> 03:16.297
They glorify unnatural sex acts.

03:16.297 --> 03:17.130
- Show me.

03:18.165 --> 03:20.468
- With so many queer creators,

03:20.468 --> 03:23.837
we see this affinity
with the shadowy margins

03:23.837 --> 03:26.006
of what's considered
respectable society.

03:26.974 --> 03:28.509
- Are you a member?

03:28.509 --> 03:30.944
- I'm looking for somebody.

03:30.944 --> 03:32.145
- Aren't we all?

03:32.145 --> 03:35.048
- The moment there's
some kind of queer lens

03:35.048 --> 03:37.050
being used to create,

03:37.050 --> 03:39.553
it immediately reflects
and reverberates

03:39.553 --> 03:41.522
throughout the piece.

03:41.522 --> 03:43.491
- The evolution of queer horror

03:43.491 --> 03:46.994
really parallels the
evolution of queer liberation.

03:46.994 --> 03:49.730
- They're waiting for you.

03:49.730 --> 03:50.664
(creature shrieks)

03:50.664 --> 03:52.800
- You begin with queer artists

03:52.800 --> 03:55.035
taking the spaces
we're allowed to have

03:55.035 --> 03:58.805
and slipping what we can
say into those spaces.

03:58.805 --> 04:01.108
* I'm afraid
there's no denyin' *

04:01.108 --> 04:03.043
* I'm just a dandy-lion

04:03.043 --> 04:06.347
- There's something affirming
about that vision in horror,

04:06.347 --> 04:07.781
because at least
we know we exist,

04:07.781 --> 04:09.317
at least we know
we are out there,

04:09.317 --> 04:10.618
even if we're only there

04:10.618 --> 04:13.853
to put the fear of God
into straight people.

04:16.324 --> 04:17.791
(woman speaks in
foreign language)

04:17.791 --> 04:20.394
- Through this material,
today's youth can be enticed

04:20.394 --> 04:23.831
to enter the world of
homosexuals, lesbians,

04:23.831 --> 04:26.300
and other sex deviants.

04:26.300 --> 04:28.602
We know that once a
person is perverted,

04:28.602 --> 04:31.572
it is practically
impossible for that person

04:31.572 --> 04:35.075
to adjust to normal
attitudes in regard to sex.

04:35.075 --> 04:37.745
(upbeat vocalization)

04:40.414 --> 04:43.183
(Jesse screams)

04:44.084 --> 04:47.020
(upbeat pop music)

05:13.981 --> 05:16.484
- We queers have been a
part of the genre of horror

05:16.484 --> 05:17.718
since the beginning, right?

05:17.718 --> 05:18.719
Since the beginning.

05:18.719 --> 05:21.722
(suspenseful music)

05:43.176 --> 05:44.578
- The horror genre as we know it

05:44.578 --> 05:47.180
really dates back to
folkloric traditions

05:47.180 --> 05:49.550
and then the gothic
tradition in literature

05:49.550 --> 05:51.552
in the 17th and 18th century.

05:52.986 --> 05:54.888
When you wanted to
write about queers,

05:54.888 --> 05:57.591
you had to find a sort
of coded way to do it.

06:00.127 --> 06:02.463
- We queers have always
had our own language.

06:04.465 --> 06:05.966
- If you know, you know,

06:05.966 --> 06:07.968
but otherwise it just kind
of goes over your head.

06:09.202 --> 06:11.572
And if somebody sees
it, it's on them.

06:11.572 --> 06:13.774
It's not quite on you.

06:13.774 --> 06:15.743
(heavy breathing)

06:15.743 --> 06:18.779
- The gothic is literally
about sublimated,

06:18.779 --> 06:20.448
hidden things coming to light.

06:22.382 --> 06:25.419
The dead, or the
past, or desires,

06:25.419 --> 06:27.254
or things that have
been pushed down.

06:28.422 --> 06:29.723
The whole point is you
can't suppress the dead,

06:29.723 --> 06:31.024
you can't suppress the past.

06:31.024 --> 06:33.794
It's always gonna
come up and erupt

06:35.162 --> 06:37.965
in some really interesting
and terrifying way.

06:37.965 --> 06:40.634
(curious music)

06:42.202 --> 06:45.238
- One of the defining
characteristics of
those gothic novels

06:45.238 --> 06:49.209
is that they are all
about transgression.

06:49.209 --> 06:52.513
Resurrecting the
dead, drinking blood,

06:52.513 --> 06:55.315
making Faustian
deals with the devil.

06:55.315 --> 07:00.287
And tied to that is, of
course, sexual transgression.

07:00.888 --> 07:02.556
(curious music)

07:02.556 --> 07:05.058
- We've now reached
a sort of stage

07:05.058 --> 07:07.861
with a very, very long
history of the gothic

07:07.861 --> 07:09.897
in literature and in film,

07:09.897 --> 07:12.633
where we can actually start to
look back at things and say,

07:12.633 --> 07:14.635
"You know, that's not quite

07:14.635 --> 07:16.403
what it appeared
to be at the time."

07:16.403 --> 07:19.473
(dark whimsical music)

07:19.473 --> 07:21.742
- The general names
from the 19th century

07:21.742 --> 07:23.944
that we associate with horror

07:23.944 --> 07:27.581
are really Bram Stoker,
Robert Louis Stevenson,

07:27.581 --> 07:29.983
but before that is Mary Shelley.

07:29.983 --> 07:32.219
- [Man] She is an angel.

07:32.219 --> 07:33.721
- You think so?

07:33.721 --> 07:37.424
- It is no surprise that a
woman created the horror genre.

07:37.424 --> 07:38.692
(thunder cracks)

07:38.692 --> 07:39.727
We're suppressed in
more ways than one,

07:39.727 --> 07:42.062
especially a queer woman.

07:42.062 --> 07:43.196
(Mary laughs)

07:43.196 --> 07:46.399
She had all the
ammunition in the world

07:46.399 --> 07:49.837
to create monsters, and she did.

07:50.871 --> 07:53.541
(heart beating)

07:57.077 --> 07:59.146
- Mary, what an icon.

07:59.146 --> 08:01.248
I'm just gonna invent science
fiction in an afternoon.

08:01.248 --> 08:02.415
Do you guys want anything?

08:02.415 --> 08:03.851
Like, "Yeah, thanks.
Thanks, Mary."

08:05.418 --> 08:10.423
- Mary Shelly is not only the
mother of the horror genre

08:11.291 --> 08:12.526
and the science fiction genre.

08:12.526 --> 08:16.363
She is a leading
feminist idealist

08:16.363 --> 08:20.367
and also the goth-est
of the goth girls.

08:20.367 --> 08:21.969
- Mary Shelley is so goth.

08:21.969 --> 08:25.238
She lost her virginity on
her mother's gravestone.

08:26.239 --> 08:27.274
- Here I come!

08:28.976 --> 08:31.144
- We all know this
image of Mary Shelley,

08:31.144 --> 08:32.212
hanging out in the graveyards,

08:32.212 --> 08:34.548
and there's a much more romantic

08:34.548 --> 08:36.082
and heartfelt way to look at it.

08:36.082 --> 08:38.719
Her mother, Mary Goodwin,
was a prolific writer

08:38.719 --> 08:40.621
before feminism was even a word,

08:40.621 --> 08:43.056
was very much so of
the feminist spirit.

08:43.056 --> 08:45.893
She died within weeks
of Mary being born.

08:45.893 --> 08:47.961
The only way for Mary Shelly

08:47.961 --> 08:50.530
to have a connection
with her mother

08:50.530 --> 08:53.466
was to be in the space
that her mother left her

08:53.466 --> 08:54.968
and to read her literature

08:54.968 --> 08:57.771
and sort of piece
together a relationship

08:57.771 --> 08:59.640
with this woman she
never got to meet.

08:59.640 --> 09:02.710
- Mary Shelly was
pretty radical.

09:02.710 --> 09:05.145
She was very sexually liberal,

09:05.145 --> 09:08.348
experimenting, very open-minded.

09:08.348 --> 09:09.917
And what was also great

09:09.917 --> 09:11.619
was just her
equality with the men

09:11.619 --> 09:13.486
that she was spending time with.

09:13.486 --> 09:16.657
- Mary Shelley was married
to Percy Bysshe Shelley.

09:16.657 --> 09:19.259
They were also part
of a who knows exactly

09:19.259 --> 09:21.261
relationship with Lord Byron.

09:21.261 --> 09:23.664
The trio was allegedly
booted out of England

09:23.664 --> 09:26.734
because of their
notorious behavior.

09:26.734 --> 09:28.936
- She was one of the
original hags, right?

09:28.936 --> 09:31.071
I mean, she could
hang out, you know?

09:31.071 --> 09:35.075
She was there for her gays,
and they were there for her.

09:35.075 --> 09:37.845
Hanging out with these
sexually fluid men

09:37.845 --> 09:40.113
and also having her own secrets

09:40.113 --> 09:42.449
really speaks to
her being a pioneer

09:42.449 --> 09:46.787
in the art of monsters and
of horror and storytelling

09:46.787 --> 09:49.522
at that time when those
stories were so new.

09:51.391 --> 09:53.126
- She's so goth.

09:53.126 --> 09:56.196
- They ended up in
Europe at Villa Diodati

09:56.196 --> 09:58.265
where they all decided
to write ghost stories

09:58.265 --> 10:00.734
fueled by drugs and
sex and alcohol.

10:00.734 --> 10:04.204
- She's really turning
it for the goths, honey.

10:04.204 --> 10:08.408
- She's 18, she's hanging out
with her husband and his bros.

10:08.408 --> 10:09.342
I shouldn't call them bros.

10:09.342 --> 10:10.543
They were all having sex.

10:10.543 --> 10:12.746
- It is an age of
dreams and nightmares.

10:12.746 --> 10:15.182
- Yes, and we are merely
the children of the age.

10:15.182 --> 10:18.351
- And she has a nightmare
about this shambling behemoth.

10:18.351 --> 10:21.088
(thunder cracks)

10:22.122 --> 10:23.590
(Mary screams)

10:23.590 --> 10:26.459
She writes it down, and she
kind of invents science fiction

10:26.459 --> 10:27.494
and horror in the same moment.

10:27.494 --> 10:29.162
(thunder cracks)
(rat squeaks)

10:29.162 --> 10:30.263
(eerie music)

10:30.263 --> 10:31.765
- As the story goes,

10:31.765 --> 10:34.868
Mary Shelley came up with
the concept of Frankenstein

10:34.868 --> 10:36.103
when she was debating,

10:36.103 --> 10:38.471
what's the scariest
story you can think of?

10:38.471 --> 10:41.008
Kind of fitting
that a female author

10:41.008 --> 10:43.911
would think the scariest
thing I can think of

10:43.911 --> 10:46.714
is a man trying to create life.

10:47.848 --> 10:50.150
- It's such a commentary
on a man's world,

10:50.150 --> 10:52.720
and it's such a commentary
on the audacity of men

10:52.720 --> 10:54.454
to think that they
could even create

10:54.454 --> 10:57.324
a functioning creature
without a woman.

10:57.324 --> 11:00.427
(eerie music)

11:00.427 --> 11:02.195
Like, the balls it
must have took for her

11:02.195 --> 11:04.031
to put those words on that page.

11:04.031 --> 11:05.899
- She's writing in an era
where there aren't a lot

11:05.899 --> 11:07.901
of female authors to begin with.

11:07.901 --> 11:09.770
It's certainly not
a respectable thing

11:09.770 --> 11:10.971
for her to be doing.

11:10.971 --> 11:12.906
Just by virtue of her
writing this book,

11:12.906 --> 11:15.308
this is like this
radical statement that,

11:15.308 --> 11:20.313
I, a bisexual woman, am capable
of these manly pursuits.

11:21.681 --> 11:23.350
- The Frankenstein monster
is literally made up

11:23.350 --> 11:26.920
of bits and pieces of other
people and other psyches,

11:26.920 --> 11:29.857
is this extraordinary outsider.

11:29.857 --> 11:33.393
- This idea that you can
recombine the elements

11:33.393 --> 11:38.131
of a human to create something
is inherently terrifying.

11:38.131 --> 11:41.601
But I think that that's sort
of what it means to be queer

11:41.601 --> 11:43.503
is you're sort of taking
all these elements

11:43.503 --> 11:47.074
of masculinity or femininity
and you're redesigning them

11:47.074 --> 11:48.742
into the person that you are.

11:49.642 --> 11:50.778
(dark playful music)

11:50.778 --> 11:52.579
- The monster chooses to attack

11:52.579 --> 11:54.581
and kill Victor
Frankenstein's wife

11:54.581 --> 11:57.584
on their wedding night so
that they never consummate.

11:57.584 --> 11:58.986
And from that point on,

11:58.986 --> 12:03.891
Victor Frankenstein is
obsessed with his male creation

12:05.292 --> 12:06.726
and is chasing the male
creation all over the world.

12:06.726 --> 12:09.429
And if that's not a queer
narrative, I don't know what is.

12:09.429 --> 12:11.799
- The literature
shows Frankenstein

12:11.799 --> 12:16.804
as so much more articulate
and smart and charismatic

12:18.138 --> 12:22.009
instead of this mumbling,
horrible creature.

12:22.009 --> 12:23.576
(The Monster whimpers)

12:23.576 --> 12:26.746
- The monster and Frankenstein
are kind of constantly

12:26.746 --> 12:29.149
ever changing, two
beings within the same

12:29.149 --> 12:30.617
that are overlapping.

12:30.617 --> 12:33.186
Frankenstein catches up with
the doctor and explains,

12:33.186 --> 12:34.955
oh yeah, I learned language.

12:34.955 --> 12:36.489
You know what I mean?

12:36.489 --> 12:39.092
Like, here I am, I'm
you, which is a monster,

12:39.092 --> 12:41.829
but I'm gonna reflect
back to you what you are.

12:45.465 --> 12:48.135
- There is something very,
very dream girls about it,

12:48.135 --> 12:50.904
of showing up at somebody's
doorstep and being like.

12:50.904 --> 12:54.274
- * And I am telling you

12:55.742 --> 12:57.210
- I am telling you
I am not going.

12:57.210 --> 12:59.746
- * I'm not going

12:59.746 --> 13:01.748
- You are going to love me and
if you're not gonna love me,

13:01.748 --> 13:03.583
